Here is the strict, command-level audit of the "Bazzite Unified Home Server + Gaming Station Guide."

General Assessment

The guide is exceptionally well-engineered. It successfully navigates complex OS-level constraints (Fedora Atomic immutability, SELinux enforcing mode, systemd-logind cgroup cleanup, and Wayland DRM master locks) to achieve a hybrid headless/graphical state. The protective sequencing—such as applying SELinux port labels before restarting SSH, and validating fstab UUIDs before writing—demonstrates a high standard of fault tolerance.

However, a strict audit reveals a few logical fragility points, particularly around disk failure states, shell string manipulation, and interactions between firewalld and Docker.

Issue Classification & Resolution
🚨 Critical Issues (System Integrity / Execution Blockers)

None found. The guide successfully avoids catastrophic failure modes. The boot chain, SSH accessibility, and base OS immutability are preserved throughout the workflow.

⚠️ Major Issues (Instability / Inconsistency Risks)

Blind Mount Vulnerability on Disk Failure (Phase 6 & 7)

State Hazard: You correctly enforce nofail in /etc/fstab so the system boots if the data drive dies. However, if the system boots without the drive, /srv/nextcloud-data remains an empty folder on the OS root filesystem.

Consequence: Because Docker Compose containers are set to restart: always, Nextcloud AIO will boot, mount the empty directory on the OS drive, and either initialize a fresh instance (overwriting your database/config) or fail due to SELinux mismatches, polluting the rootfs.

Recovery/Fix: Make the mount point immutable when unmounted. Run sudo chattr +i /srv/nextcloud-data before mounting the drive in Phase 6. If the drive fails to mount, Docker will be denied write access to the immutable folder, intentionally crashing the container and protecting the system state.

🔍 Minor Issues (Efficiency, Clarity, & Syntax Fragility)

Syntax Fragility in Drive Partitioning (Phase 6, Step 1)

Logic Gap: The variable assignment DATA_PART="${DATA_DRIVE}p1" # NVMe — if SATA/USB use: "${DATA_DRIVE}1" relies on the user reading the comment and manually editing the command. A blind copy-paste for a SATA drive (e.g., /dev/sdb) executes sudo mkfs.ext4 /dev/sdbp1, which fails.

Fix: Replace manual string manipulation with a deterministic dynamic lookup:
DATA_PART=$(lsblk -rn -o NAME "$DATA_DRIVE" | tail -n 1 | awk '{print "/dev/"$1}')

Interactive visudo Trap for Beginners (Phase 8, Step 5)

Assumption: sudo visudo -f /etc/sudoers.d/session-scripts drops the user into an interactive editor (vi or nano). The instruction "Paste these three lines" assumes terminal editor proficiency.

Fix: Make the command fully non-interactive and deterministic:

code
Bash
download
content_copy
expand_less
echo -e "$USER ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD: /usr/local/bin/start-kde.sh\n$USER ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD: /usr/local/bin/start-gaming.sh\n$USER ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD: /usr/local/bin/stop-session.sh" | sudo tee /etc/sudoers.d/session-scripts > /dev/null
sudo visudo -c -f /etc/sudoers.d/session-scripts

Firewalld vs. Docker nftables Conflict (Phase 4)

Hidden Transition: The guide correctly notes that Docker bypasses firewalld for ports 80/443. However, if a user runs sudo firewall-cmd --reload after Phase 7 (when containers are active), firewalld will completely flush Docker's dynamically injected nftables routing rules, breaking external access to Nextcloud.

Fix: Add a strict warning in Appendix B: Never reload firewalld while Docker is running. If you must, run sudo systemctl restart docker immediately afterward to restore network rules.

Redundant Apache Binding (Phase 7, Step 3)

Logic Check: APACHE_IP_BINDING=127.0.0.1 binds Nextcloud's port to the host's loopback interface. While this provides defense-in-depth, Nginx Proxy Manager (in Phase 10) connects to Nextcloud via the internal Docker network (nextcloud-aio-apache:11000), not via the host's loopback. The host bind is technically unnecessary but does no harm.

Element Classification

Essential:

Masking Suspend Targets (Phase 1): Bazzite aggressively suspends inactive systems. This is mandatory.

SELinux Labeling Before SSH Restart (Phase 4): A flawless, mandatory sequence. Restarting sshd on port 53222 without this label results in immediate, irreversible remote lockout.

systemd-run --collect in Session Scripts (Phase 8): Brilliant engineering. Bypassing systemd-logind's KillUserProcesses=yes by escaping the SSH cgroup into a transient system-level service guarantees the headless state restores after the user disconnects.

Optional:

Fail2ban (Phase 4): With PasswordAuthentication no and SSH moved off port 22, the server is already mathematically immune to brute-force and hidden from 99% of automated scanners. Fail2ban acts purely as log-noise reduction here.

krdp / SSH Tunneling (Phase 9): Useful, but strictly optional if the user only intends to use the physical display for Gaming Mode.

Unnecessary:

Manual whoami checks: The guide asks the user to run whoami and replace yourusername. Using the $USER shell variable in all script generation (tee / cat >) would eliminate manual text substitution and prevent user typos.

Final Validation Checklist

To confirm the system has successfully reached the intended, secure, deterministic end-state, verify the following absolute truths via SSH:

[ ] Headless Guard Check: Run cat /etc/sddm.conf.d/zzz-headless-server.conf. It must exist, and User= must be strictly empty.

[ ] Port Security Check: Run ss -tlnp | grep sshd. It must only return *:53222. Port 22 must be entirely dead.

[ ] Immutability Bypass Check: Run rpm-ostree status. docker-ce must appear under LayeredPackages.

[ ] Service Routing Check: Run curl -I http://localhost:8081. It must return HTTP/1.1 302 Found (Nginx Proxy Manager), proving the Docker network and web UI are successfully bound to loopback.

[ ] Cgroup Escape Test: Run sudo start-kde.sh, then immediately type exit to close the SSH session. Wait 10 seconds, reconnect via SSH, and run loginctl list-sessions. You should see the active KDE session, proving the transient timer survived the SSH disconnection.

Final Rating

Score: 9.5 / 10

This is an elite-tier configuration guide. It handles the quirks of immutable Linux (Fedora Atomic), Wayland DRM master contention, and Systemd cgroups with deep technical accuracy. It avoids the common trap of telling users to disable SELinux, instead properly utilizing semanage port and fcontext. The deduction of 0.5 points is solely for the blind-mount vulnerability in fstab/Docker and the minor syntax fragilities that could trip up an absolute beginner during copy-pasting.
